<p>Days of torrential rain triggered floods and landslides across much of Mexico, killing at least 41 people, damaging thousands of homes, cutting power to entire towns, and isolating some communities [dw.com#1][nytimes.com#2][lemonde.fr#3]. The heaviest impacts were reported in central and southeastern regions, though authorities and reporters describe disruption across nearly the entire country [abcnews.go.com#4][firstpost.com#5][lemonde.fr#3]. The government has deployed thousands of troops to clear blocked roads and assist in rescue operations nationwide [dw.com#1][firstpost.com#5]. Forecasters warned that more rain was expected over the weekend, complicating recovery efforts [nytimes.com#2]. Earlier official tallies put the death toll at 37 before rising as assessments continued [abcnews</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/OEkzo2ggMBTOd7DWEXhtlivS0QrUWr15liGrIIl1-861tbC6sAJROZDDBIHNMbmPPBiCiuDn64RCWUwqPL6AGmgVdde4C0u0nT_GBbDeFmFmbhXYpaIijzQK2KHJl5mLh_kEbAhNT-tqKhmN-fyPnoyoSWCl0-AT2vPYdPo0DRT6rliLQJ-7vQ' alt='Heavy rain in Mexico has left dozens dead.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Casualty update: Authorities and media report at least 41 deaths, up from earlier counts of 37 as conditions worsened [dw.com#1][nytimes.com#2][lemonde.fr#3][abcnews.go.com#4][firstpost.com#5].</li><li>Widespread damage: Thousands of homes were damaged and entire towns lost power, with some communities cut off by floodwaters and landslides [nytimes.com#2][lemonde.fr#3].</li><li>Government response: Thousands of troops were deployed to clear roads and support rescues across affected areas [dw.com#1][firstpost.com#5].</li><li>Geographic spread: Central and southeastern Mexico were hit hard, with reports of flooding and landslides across nearly the whole country [abcnews.go.com#4][lemonde.fr#3].</li><li>Continued rainfall: More rain was expected over the weekend, raising concerns about continued disruptions [nytimes.com#2].</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.